FCC says:
The last challenge showed an example of the justify-content property. 
For the tweet embed, this property can be applied to align the items in the .profile-name element.

The initial code:
<style>
  body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  }
  header, footer {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: row;
  }
  header .profile-thumbnail {
    width: 50px;
    height: 50px;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }
  header .profile-name {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;

    margin-left: 10px;
  }
  header .follow-btn {
    display: flex;
    margin: 0 0 0 auto;
  }
  header .follow-btn button {
    border: 0;
    border-radius: 3px;
    padding: 5px;
  }
  header h3, header h4 {
    display: flex;
    margin: 0;
  }
  #inner p {
    margin-bottom: 10px;
    font-size: 20px;
  }
  #inner hr {
    margin: 20px 0;
    border-style: solid;
    opacity: 0.1;
  }
  footer .stats {
    display: flex;
    font-size: 15px;
  }
  footer .stats strong {
    font-size: 18px;
  }
  footer .stats .likes {
    margin-left: 10px;
  }
  footer .cta {
    margin-left: auto;
  }
  footer .cta button {
    border: 0;
    background: transparent;
  }
</style>

The task required me to add the CSS property justify-content to the header's .profile-name element 
and set the value to any of the options from the last challenge.

This was my code:
header .profile-name {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    justify-content: space-between;
    margin-left: 10px;
  }
  
You should see the change reflect in your testing environment.
You can also use any of the other values to see different changes:
center, flex-start, flex-end, space-around, or space-evenly.
